Abstract

Climate change has a strange way of impacting different altitudinal regions. Here in Colorado, one week itâs 75 degrees and the next week itâs snowing. So, what if we compared Denver, CO to a low altitude place that is commonly warm year-round, like New Orleans, LA. Using RStudio, we made visualizations of comparisons between the two cities in multiple different aspects using multiple different forms. These visualizations were able to give us a good picture of how different the two places are impacted by climate change. For our project we found most of our data from the NOAA website and were able to manipulate the data to fit the time frames needed. We also made sure to manipulate the data to make sure there was no missing or empty data place. These datasets included temperature, elevation, humidity, and urban heat. We performed several analyses for our project, comparing different components of our data. Our time series analysis showed upward trends in temperature for warm days in both Denver and New Orleans with Denver having colder winters. A multi-line time series plot compared humidity between the cities, with New Orlenas having higher humidity across all months and times a day. Compared to Denver, peaking at selective months. A multiple linear regression showed how elevation and temperature had a strong correlation. Finally, we conducted an Exploratory Data Analysis comparing minimum and maximum temperatures, average, and extreme minimum and maximum. Both cities show long-term changes in climate patterns.

Introduction

How much does the temperature in high altitude areas (Denver CO) differ from low altitude areas (New Orleans LA)? It might not seem too different when youâre within 1000 feet of each other, but what happens when itâs a 5000 feet difference between one elevation and another? We wanted our data to look at the extremes of elevation so we can see if there really is a difference in temperature between high and low elevations. So we decided to pick Colorado, the highest elevation in the US (OâNeill, 2024), and New Orleans, one of the lowest elevations in the US (OâNeill, 2024). According to (âHow Global Temperature and Weather Patterns Affect Mountain Climates,â 2024), higher altitude regions tend to respond to climate change in complex ways. Being able to track these interesting changes will provide us with data to help people understand why high and low elevations are impacted by climate change differently. If we manage climate change the same in both regions, we might not be helping anyone because the two areas are affected by climate change so differently. The data we have will help us understand the highly impacted areas that might be suffering from the impacts of climate change more than other areas. Another reason why this topic is important to study is the fact that higher altitude areas are more sensitive to climate shifts (ITT_User, 2023). With the climate shifting rapidly, there is much research to be done to see how sensitive these areas are and in what aspect. We will also be including Urban Heat Island effects in Denver and New Orleans. The UHI effect is important to include because at lower elevations, it is probably more humid and has lots of concrete, which makes the summers much hotter. So, the urban heat island effect might have New Orleans warming faster than Denver. Lastly, high altitudes contribute to climate variability and play a role in atmospheric circulation patterns (ITT_User, 2023) so there could be much more effected by the altitudes than just the climate. In this project, we will be creating visualizations to show what climatic variables are making high and low altitudes respond differently to climate change.

Methods

We started the project with collecting all the data we needed to be able to successfully show how climate change impacted the two different regions. Thankfully, we were able to find all our data within the NOAA website. Most of the data was in the âComparative Climatic Dataâ section of NOAA (âNational Centers for Environmental Information,â 2025), the denver_neworleans.csv was found in the âClimate Data Online Searchâ section of NOAA (Matters, 2023). Lastly, we needed elevation data, which we collected from the USGS website (Eastern Region Geography, 2001). After we collected all the data, we needed to see if the data had any missing values. We went through each dataset in excel and replaced the missing values with NAâs and made sure the column names all matched up in each dataset. Then, we transported the data to RStudio in a csv form. We renamed all the dataset so we could keep track of them and so they would be easier to use in code. The data we obtained and the names we used for them were: cold_days.csv: Number of days with minimum temperature â¤ 32Â°F, denver_neworleans.csv: Annual temperature data from 2000-2020 for New Orleans and Denver, elevation.csv: Elevation data with the peaks and dips of the major US cities, hightest_temp.csv: Highest recorded temperature per month, hot_days.csv: Number of days with maximum temperature â¥ 90Â°F, humidity.csv: Annual relative humidity by location, lowest_temp.csv: Lowest recorded temperature per month, nrmavg.csv: Normal daily average temperature, nrmmax.csv: Normal daily maximum temperature, nrmmin.csv: Normal daily minimum temperature, and UHI.csv: Urban heat island effect in 2023 for each city in the US. Each dataset included location information like city, station_ID, or state, then date/year, and the measurement of interest. We then decided to make many visualizations. (1) a line plot comparing humidity between Denver and New Orleans, (2) a bar plot comparing hot and cold days in Denver vs New Orleans, (3) a liner regression model showing elevation vs average annual temperature in Denver vs New Orleans, and (4) a linear regression model showing urban heat index effect vs average annual temperature in Denver vs New Orleans.

EDA of Denver vs New Orleans temperatures

We are using a exploratory data analysis to explore temperature-related variables across both Denver and New Orleans over the years. The key temperature measurements we included were: EMINT = extreme min temperature (averaged annually), EMAXT = extreme max temperature (averaged annually), TAVG = normal temperature (averaged annually), TMAX = max temperature (averaged annually), TMIN = min temperature (averaged annually), DT32 = days where the temperature is less than 32Â°F, DX90 = days where the temperature is greater than or equal to 90Â°F. The data for these variables were split by city (Denver and New Orleans) and visualized for each year, showing trends for each measurement type over time.

After analyzing the trend lines (created from linear smoothing), we can see that Denver has steady fluctuations when it comes to extreme minimum and maximum temperatures over the years. The temperature maximums, minimums, and days 90Â°F or above have similar upward trends. But, days below 32Â°F have been slowly decreasing overtime. Then, going to the New Orleans graphs, all of the graphs have a steep upward slant excluding the days below 32Â°F.

Relationship Between Elevation, Urban Heat Island Effect, and Average Temperature

We analyzed how elevation and the urban heat island (UHI) effect influence average annual temperature (TAVG) across Denver and New Orleans using a multiple linear regression model.


Call:
lm(formula = TAVG ~ Elevation_ft + UHI_Effect, data = final_data_clean)

The model showed that elevation was a significant predictor of temperature. In the linear regression analysis of temperature over time, Denver had a p-value of 0.407, indicating no statistically significant warming trend. In contrast, New Orleans had a p-value less than 0.001, suggesting that average temperatures there are steadily increasing. In the multiple linear regression model relating temperature to elevation and UHI effect, only elevation was a statistically significant predictor (p < 0.001). UHI_effect was not calculated due to its correlation with elevation and temperature. The model had a very high explanatory power (R-squared = 0.985), indicating that variation in temperature was nearly fully explained by elevation alone.

Discussion/Conclusion

Our goal of this study was to understand how climate change affects temperatures at different altitudes. We did this by comparing annual temperature changes in Denver, Colorado (high elevation) and New Orleans, Louisiana (low elevation). Our hypothesis was that we expected to see a notable difference in temperature trend between the two cities. After our analyses we found that both cities are experiencing an increase in temperature, but New Orleans is rising at a faster rate than Denver. This can show the connection between temperature change and altitude. This conclusion can also includes the fact that urbanized and humid regions are more vulnerable to warming. Areas like this are also more susceptible to warming due to Urban Heat Island effect and lack of snow cover compared to areas like Denver. Increased temperatures can lead to greater health risks as well as ecosystem changes(âHeat and Health,â 2024). Policies may be implemented to slow the warming, but they may cause unrest and disagreement amongst people. There is also no single strategy that works for all areas due to different fluctuations depending on the region. Our studies seem to align with many other research findings. It seems to be common that elevation influences temperature, but these studies also agree that there are several other factors involved. Altitude has a significant influence on how regions experience changes in climate. When we compared Denver and New Orleans, we found that both cities have been continuously warming over the last two decades. We found that these changes vary depending on factors like intensity, Urban Heat Island effect, altitude, and humidity. Denver does not seem to be affected the same way New Orleans is affected by climate change. Our results draw to the importance of mitigation and implementation of climate strategies. It is important to do more research on climate affects in higher altitude regions. It is said that âaccelerating mountain climate change has extensive environmental impacts, including depletion of snow/ice reserves, critical for the worlds water supplyâ (Pepin et al., 2022). This is important to include, even though it was not included in our research because it just shows how different higher altitudes are impacted compared to lower altitudes. Lower altitudes seem to suffer from temperature warming while higher altitudes seem to be suffering from snow melt/ice depletions which makes sense why Denver remains cooler and its increase in temperature trend over time was not as extreme as New Orleans.
